# Getting started

In this demo, we will demonstrate how to make an R Markdown-based personal website
and publishing the website on GitHub pages.

Before we get started, decide what directory on your computer you would like your
website to live. For me, my website will be in `~/tmp/website`.

Open the R console and set your working directory to your selected directory.

```{r}
setwd("~/tmp/website")
```

## Create website skeleton

We will create a website skeleton using a baked-in command from the `rmarkdown` package.

* Note the use of `:::` in the command below.

```{r}
rmarkdown:::site_skeleton(getwd())
```

This will create three files:

* `_site.yml`: this is a file we will edit to control meta-features of the website
* `about.Rmd` and `index.Rmd`: these are just template files for pages on the website

The basic design of an R Markdown website is to have a `_site.yml` file that controls
much of the appearance of the website (e.g., the navigation bar, the website theme, 
directories where files are found/saved, etc...).

Otherwise, each page within the website is created using an `.Rmd` file.

## Create R Project

Let's go ahead and make this directory an R Project, because R Studio tends to play
more nicely with R Projects.

To do this, go to File: New Project: From Existing Directory and then select the 
directory where your website lives.

R Studio should be smart enough to figure out that this directory is a website. You can 
confirm this by looking at the contents of the `website.Rproj` file. For example, you could
open your Terminal, set working directory to your website directory and execute the following command. You will need to replace `website.Rproj` with the name of your 
`.Rproj` file name.

```{bash}
cat website.Rproj
```

## Change output directory

This step is not strictly necessary, but is helpful for keeping things tidy.

Open the `_site.yml` file and add the following line at the end.

```{yaml}
output_dir: docs
```

Recall that GitHub pages likes looking in a folder called `docs` to find `.html` 
files that it serves on a GitHub pages website.

We don't edit/modify directly whats in the docs file It will change from what you do in the yaml (or other files?). 

All of the files in doc folder will need to be committed to github. 

## Render the site locally

We will use a command in the R console to build your website. Open the R Console
and execute the following command.

```{r}
rmarkdown::render_site()
```

Check the `docs` folder of your project directory. You should see:

* `about.html` and `index.html`: these are the rendered `html` documents that make up your website
* `site_libs` directory: this contains all the extra bells and whistles that are needed to make your website look pretty on GitHub pages.

All of these files will need to be committed and pushed to GitHub to get your website working.

## Turn off jekyll

In prepartion for pushing to GitHub, we will add an empty file named `.nojekyll` to your project. This can be done via the Terminal.

```{bash}
touch .nojekyll
```

This is not strictly necessary, but it may slightly speed up website deployment when you push new material to GitHub. The presence of this file tells GitHub pages that it doesn't need to rebuild any part of the website before serving the site.

Read more about `jekyll` [here](https://docs.github.com/en/pages/setting-up-a-github-pages-site-with-jekyll).


## Initialize git

Open a terminal, make sure your working directory is set to your project's root directory and execute the following command.

```{bash}
git init
```

This initializes a git repository. Let's go ahead and create a `.gitignore` file. As in DATA 550, I like to do this using `touch`. 

```{bash}
touch .gitignore
```

Open the `.gitignore` file and add the `.Rproj.user` directory to the `.gitignore`. I will also go ahead and add the `.DS_Store` file that Macs love to create to my `.gitignore` as well. Prior to saving, my `.gitignore` will look like this.

```{bash}
.Rproj.user/*
.DS_Store
```

Now, we can go ahead and make our first commit.

```{bash}
git add --all
git commit -m "first commit"
```

## Initialize GitHub repository

Now hop over to [Github](https://github.com) and create a new repository. Do not initialize with a README and a `.gitignore`. 

Add your GitHub repository as a remote and push using the `ssh` protocol.

```{bash}
git remote add origin git@github.com:benkeser/example_website
git push origin main
```

## Create GitHub pages website

In your web browser, navigate to your GitHub repository.

Click on Settings. Then on the left hand side of the screen, look under `Code and automation` and click on `Pages`.

Leave `Source` set to `Deploy from a branch`.

Under `Branch`, select `main`, select the `docs` folder, and click `Save`.

Your website is now live at https://yourusername.github.io/yourreponame. You can visit that website to confirm.

You can add this website address to your repo description so that it's easy to find.

# Personalizing your website

## General workflow

We will now make some updates to personalize your website. The general workflow for updating your site is as follows:

* Update source code (i.e., `.Rmd` or `_site.yml` files)
* Compile the website using `rmarkdown::render_site()` to generate new `.html` files
* Open `docs/index.html` to preview website
* When satisfied with appearance, `git commit` and `git push` to update the website online

What you see locally will be what you see on GitHub. If the website renders differently online vs. locally, then there is likely an issue of not pushing updated `site_libs` to GitHub. 

In general, you will not want to update the compiled source code (i.e., the `.html` files in the `docs` folder) directly.

## Updating the home page

Let's add a picture of yourself to the home page. First, make an `images` directory.

```{bash}
mkdir images
```

Move a picture of yourself to this directory. My picture will be called `profile.png`.

Add a code chunk to `index.Rmd`

````markdown
`r ''````{r, echo=FALSE, fig.align='center', out.width='40%'}
knitr::include_graphics("images/profile.png")
```
````

Note that we used `out.width='40%'` to specify relative width of the image. This allows the image to scale with different sized browsers

Getting an image to look nice on a website across all possible devices typically requires:

* Reasonably high resolution image
* Moving away from using just `markdown` to style your page and instead writing `html` and/or `css` directly

Note: when you re-build the website, R Markdown will create a copy of your `images` directory in the `docs` folder. In general, R Markdown will put any referenced files into the `docs` directory. 

* This creates some redundancy, but that is ok unless you are uploading very large files. 
* It enables a simple workflow wherein you only edit files in your projects root directory and *never* directly modify files in `docs`.

## Adding columns to the homepage

Let's change the layout of the homepage to have two columns. This is something we will (for now) achieve directly with (mostly) `markdown` syntax.

Add the following to `index.Rmd`.

````
::: columns
::: {.column width="50%" style="text-align: center;"}

`r ''````{r, echo=FALSE, fig.align='center', out.width='100%'}
knitr::include_graphics("images/profile.png")
```

## Your Name

:::

::: {.column width="50%" style="text-align: left;"}

Add some text here describing yourself. Add a [link](https://google.com) so we can see behavior later. 

:::
````

A few notes: 
* The above is mostly using Markdown syntax; however, some `css` has crept into the code -- this is the `style="text-align: left;"` bit above. 
* Notice we have changed `out.width='100%'` in order for the image to span the entire left column.

You can play around a bit with the formatting, but note that the columns do not have the best "reactive" behavior. If you view them on a narrow device, the text will get smaller so that everything fits on the screen. Nicer behavior might be to have the columns stack on top of one another. This would require integrating raw html and/or css, which we discuss later.

## Updating the About page

We will make some light edits to the About page to include some basic information about yourself. 

Remove the auto-generated content and add a few sentences about yourself (e.g., your education background, current jobs, interests, etc...)

## Updating the navigation bar

Let's now update the navigation bar to include some links to "socials". We will do this by updating the `_site.yml` file. I will add a link to my Github. Other links you might want to include:

* Email (beware spam if listing on a website)
* Google scholar profile
* Bluesky/X (if that's your thing)
* ORCID
* Linked In

Open the `_site.yml` file and modify the `navbar` section it so it looks like this:

````markdown
navbar:
  left:
  - text: Home
    href: index.html
    icon: fa-home
  - text: About
    href: about.html
    icon: fa-book-open
  right:
  - href: https://github.com/benkeser
