# Styling your website

Now that the basic workflow for adding and doing light styling of pages is done, let's see how to make the website look fancier using themes and custom `css` files.

## Add a site theme

The most straightforward way to update the entire appearance of your website is to select a [Bootstrap theme](https://getbootstrap.com/).

To do this update your `_site.yml` file to include a section specifying the theme.

````markdown
output:
  html_document:
    theme: yeti
````

There are several default themes:

* `default`, `cerulean`, `journal`, `flatly`, `darkly`, `readable`, `spacelab`, `united`, `cosmo`, `lumen`, `paper`, `sandstone`, `simplex`, and `yeti` (use `null` for no theme)

Adding `type: inverse` below the `theme` line can sometimes change the appearance of each theme as well.

Note: R Markdown websites using Bootstrap version 3. As of the writing of this document, Bootstrap is available up to version 5 with additional features and themes. Use [`quarto` websites](https://quarto.org/docs/websites/) to leverage more recent versions of Bootstrap.

## Add custom css

Cascading Style Sheets (`css`) controls how html content looks. We use `css` to change colors, fonts, spacing, layout, and other design aspects.

*Selectors* and *rules* are the core structure of `css`.

* You target elements of your webpage (e.g., `p`, `.class`, `#id`) and define style rules for each element inside braces (e.g., `color`, `font-size`, `margin`).

"Cascading" means that there styles can come from multiple places (browser defaults, external stylesheets, inline styles) and there is a priority for which are used.

We have already been using `css` under the hood. E.g., Bootstrap is basically just a style sheet that is set up to control each of the elements of your webpage.

Check out `docs/site_libs/bootstrap-3.3.5/css/bootstrap.css` to see what it looks like. This document is far more complex than what we will use "by hand", but it gives you a flavor for what `css` looks like.

If there is a particular element you would like to change, rather than modifying the `bootstrap.css` file, we can add a new *style sheet* to our webpage.

Let's create a new file called `style.css`.

```bash
touch style.css
```

Open this file in R Studio and add the following.

```{css}
/* Default link color */
a {
  color: #2C7BE5;  /* pick your favorite color for links */
  text-decoration: none;
}

/* Hover state */
a:hover {
  color: #1A5BB8;  /* pick your favorite color for links when mouse hovers */
  text-decoration: underline;
}
```

Here, we are just adding two simple custom styles to our website that define the appearance and behavior of links.

Some notes:

* `a` is the html element for links. So we are saying select all links and apply the following rules for styling them.
* `color` and `text-decoration` are two style elements that we are controlling
* All styles for a given target appear between curly braces and all lines end with a semi-colon.
* We are specifying the color in hexidecimal format. You can use [free color pickers](https://www.color-hex.com/) to get the hex code for colors that you like.

In general, LLM's are reasonably good at generating css if you are able to precisely describe the behavior that you want. Use this to your advantage, but double check that output behaves as expected!

## Add google font

We can also add custom fonts using [Google fonts](https://fonts.google.com). Visit this website to pick a font that you like. Make sure it is a freely available font!

When you have identified a font that you like:

* Click on the font
* Click `Get font` in the upper right corner
* Click `< > Get embed code`
* Click `@import`
* Copy the `@import` line that is shown. You do not need to copy the `<style>` and `</style>` tags

For example, if I was importing the Lato font, I would copy:

````markdown
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Lato:ital,wght@0,100;0,300;0,400;0,700;0,900;1,100;1,300;1,400;1,700;1,900&family=Raleway:ital,wght@0,100..900;1,100..900&display=swap');
````

Add this line to the top of `style.css`.

Note: this technically imports all versions of the font. If you want ever so slightly faster loading, you could uncheck some of the boxes on the left of the page before generating the embed code.

Now add the following chunk to your `style.css` in order to use this font through the body of your document.

```{css}
body {
    font-family: 'Lato';
}
```

Note: if you picked a different font, you would need to reference that font instead of `Lato` in the above. 

Here we are telling web browsers to render the entire `body` of the html document with this font. If you instead only want to change the font of certain elements, you would include the `font-family` style tag in an entry for those targets.

You could also add additional style tags to this if you would like. E.g., adding `font-size: 19px;` will make the font larger. 

## Style the project page using html

So far we have been styling using markdown syntax. It is also possible to directly include html. Here, we give one example of that by styling the project page to include `cards` for each project. 

We are going to replace the contents of the Projects page with the following raw `html`.

```{html}
<div class="row">

<div class="col-sm-6">
<a href="https://bit.ly/info550" class="project-link">
<div class="panel panel-default">
<div class="panel-heading">
<h3 class="panel-title">DATA 550 website</h3>
</div>
<div class="panel-body">
<p>A Jekyll website I built for previous iterations of this class.</p>
</div>
</div>
</a>
</div>
<div class="col-sm-6">
<a href="https://github.com/allicodi/vaxstrat" class="project-link">
<div class="panel panel-default">
<div class="panel-heading">
<h3 class="panel-title">vaxstrat R package</h3>
</div>
<div class="panel-body">
<p>An R package for computing principal effects quantifying vaccine impact on post-infection endpoints.</p>
</div>
</div>
</a>
</div>
</div>
```

A few notes:

* Markdown parsing is a little bit annoying here and seems to require no indentation to recognize that this is raw html. It makes the formatting a little annoying.
* We are using Bootstrap [`panels`](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/3.4/components/#panels) to format our projects.
* The `col-sm-6` allows for dynamic resizing and stacking of elements.

This could be further styled as desired using `css`.


## Add a favicon

A final finishing touch is to add a favicon -- the icon that you see in a browser tab for your website.

You can either use an image that you have generated or use a [favicon generator](https://favicon.io/). Save the image as a `.png` or a `.ico` and place it in your projects `images` directory.

Create a new file called `header.html` in your project root directory.

```{bash}
touch header.html
```

Add the following contents.

```{html}
<link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="images/favicon.ico"/>
```

Update your `_site.yml` file to look like this:

````markdown
output:
  html_document:
    theme: yeti
    css: style.css
    includes: 
      in_header: header.html
````

Re-build the website and you should see the favicon appear!

To finalize the project, commit all the new files and push to GitHub!